{"title_page": "Ohmdenosaurus", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|fossil_range = [[Toarcian]], {{fossil range|180}}\n|image =Ohmdenosaurus.JPG\n|image_caption = Fossil tibia and astragalus\n|genus = Ohmdenosaurus\n|species = liasicus\n|authority = Wild, 1978\n}}\n\n'''''Ohmdenosaurus''''' (meaning \"Ohmden lizard\") is a [[genus]] of [[herbivorous]] [[dinosaur]] from the Lower or middle [[Toarcian]] stage of the Early [[Jurassic]] from what is now [[Ohmden]], [[Germany]]. It is one of the earliest representatives of the [[Sauropoda|sauropods]] group of [[Europe]], with dubious representatives known by footprints from the [[Sinemurian]] of [[Romania]],<ref>G. Pienkowski, M. E. Popa, and A. Kedzior. 2009. Early Jurassic sauropod footprints of the Southern Carpathians, Romania: palaeobiological and palaeogeographical significance. Geological Quarterly 53(4):461-470</ref> [[Poland]]<ref>G. Gierlinski. 1991. New dinosaur ichnotaxa from the Early Jurassic of the Holy Cross Mountains, Poland. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology 85:137\u2013148</ref> or [[Italy]],<ref>M. Avanzini and G. Leonardi. 1993. Dinosauri nel Trentino: il giacimento dei Lavini di Marco [Dinosaurs in Trentino: the locality of Lavini di Marco]. UCT (Uomo - Citt\u00e0 - Territorio) 214:35-41</ref> bing an exceptional discovery, since late Liassic dinosaurs tend to be a rare thing, especially in Europe. It is also currently one of the few [[Sauropoda|sauropods]] described from the [[Toarcian]] of the modern northern hemisphere, along with ''[[Tazoudasaurus]]'' which has been considered a relative. ''Ohmdenosaurus'' lived on an island series in what is now the region of [[Bohemia]]. It was mistaken originally as a plesiosaur remains, until a revision of the holotype in 1978. It is the only dinosaur identified from the [[Posidonia Shale]].<ref name=\"wild1978\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Ohmdenosaurus Scale.svg|thumb|300px|left|Scaled type specimen]] \n''Ohmdenosaurus'' is considered a primitive sauropod, although not the most known one. Following the Sauropod morphological trend, it is believed that its appearance would be that of a fully quadrupedal animal, with a long neck and a relatively robust body. It is not really known the range of specialization of primitive sauropods referred to its diet, being herbivorous, but probably with different choices concerning the type of vegetation. ''Ohmdenosaurus'' probably ranged from medium to high vegetation, with plants like tall [[Bennettitales]], [[Araucariaceae]] and [[Podocarpaceae]] trees being among the most probably components of its diet.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The type specimen of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' consists on a [[Tibia]] and a [[Talus bone]] (Astragalus). The Tibia possesses a bent and sloping, powerful [[Cnemial Crest]], that is delimited laterally by a sulcus; it has a proximal joint end,  perpendicular to the longitudinal axis of the shaft; the lateral part of the tibia has a lateral crista that extends to the middle; The Astragalus is flat in comparison to the Tibia, with a sandal-shaped form, without ascending process; calcaneus has small proportions, and is disc-shaped.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The articulation presents a possible joint with bony sesamoids, but that wasn't compared.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The size of the Tibia is 405&nbsp;mm long according to Wild<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> and Carrano (1998),<ref>Carrano, M. T. (1998). The evolution of dinosaur locomotion: biomechanics, functional morphology, and modern analogs (Doctoral dissertation, Ph. D. thesis. University of Chicago, Chicago, Ill).</ref> with an estimated femur length of at least 70&nbsp;cm. This yielded traditionally an estimated total body length of {{Convert|4|m|ft|abbr=on}}. This is relatively small for a sauropod.<ref name=\"wild1978\" /><ref name=\"Upchurch, P. 1995\">Upchurch, P. (1995). The evolutionary history of sauropod dinosaurs. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B: Biological Sciences, 349(1330), 365\u2013390.</ref> The small size of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' led to speculate that the taxon may have been one of the few examples on insular dwarfism on Sauropods, being a similar case to that of the also German [[Late Jurassic]] Macronarian [[Europasaurus]]. That was recovered on several books and studies, although it has not been proved.<ref>Gro\u00dfmann, F. (2006). Taxonomy, Phylogeny and Palaeoecology of the Plesiosauroids (sauropterygia, Reptilia) from the Posidonia Shale (Toarcian, Lower Jurassic) of Holzmaden, South West Germany: Dissertation Zur Erlangung Des Grades Eines Doktors Der Naturwissenschaften (p. 135). Geowissenschaftlichen Fakult\u00e4t der Eberhard-Karls-Universit\u00e4t.</ref>''Ohmdenosaurus'' has been suggested as a juvenile individual on several encyclopedias, although there has not been any osteological study to prove it.<ref>Mclntosh, J. S. (1997). M. K. Brett-Surman, and James O. Farlow. The Complete Dinosaur, 264.</ref><ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{Cite book | last1 = Holtz | first1 = Thomas R., Jr. | last2 = Rey | first2 = Luis V. | title = Dinosaurs: the most complete, up-to-date encyclopedia for dinosaur lovers of all ages | url = https://archive.org/details/dinosaursmostcom00holt | year = 2007 | publisher = Random House | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-375-82419-7 | access-date = 2012-01-26 | url-status = live }}</ref> Molina P\u00e9rez & Larramendi, stated that the sauropod was \"downgraded\" in size, with an unexplained reduction when a femur of 70&nbsp;cm is suggested. They suggested a new size of 6.7 m long, with a weight of 1.3 tonnes. The last estimation, however, should be taken with caution, as the specimen would need an \"in-depth\" revision, as is based on a not concretely estimated tibia.<ref>Molina-P\u00e9rez, R., & Larramendi, A. (2020). Dinosaur Facts and Figures: The Sauropods and Other Sauropodomorphs. Princeton University Press.</ref>\n\n==History of discovery==\nIn the 1970s, German [[palaeontologist]] Rupert Wild, visiting the [[Urwelt-Museum Hauff]] at [[Holzmaden]] in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], noticed a fossil in a display labelled as an [[humerus|upper arm bone]] of a [[plesiosaur]] which he recognized as a misidentified dinosaur fossil.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The bone had been collected from one of the early quarries near [[Ohmden]] that was later refilled. Although the exact discovery site is unknown, rock attached to the lower end of the fossil comes from the ''unterer Schiefer'' (\"lower slate\"), the oldest part of the [[Posidonia Shale]].<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> It is therefore Early [[Toarcian]] in age (182.0 to 175.6 mya).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicTaxonInfo?taxon_no=65914|publisher=[[Paleobiology Database]]|website=paleobiodb.org|access-date=2019-08-04|title=''Ohmdenosaurus liasicus'' Wild 1978 (sauropod)}}</ref>\nFurther study determined that the fossil belonged to a new genus and species of early sauropod, which Wild named ''Ohmdenosaurus liasicus'' in a 1978 publication. The fossil, which lacks an inventory number, consists of a right [[tibia]] (shinbone) together with the upper bones of the ankle, the [[Talus bone|astragalus]] and the [[calcaneus]]. The bones, disarticulated in the fossil, show signs of weathering, evidence that the animal died on land and that only later were its bones washed into the sea.\n\n== Classification ==\nThe shape of the astragalus - which is not convex on top as it is in derived members of [[Neosauropoda]] - suggests that ''Ohmdenosaurus'' was a very basal sauropod, although with the finds on new groups such as [[Lessemsauridae]] the status of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' has slightly changed, being seen as a less basal taxon, related in most of the contemporaneous works to the [[Gravisauria]]ns. In 1990 John Stanton McIntosh included ''Ohmdenosaurus'' in the [[Vulcanodontidae]]<ref>McIntosh,  J.S.,  1990.  Sauropoda.  In:  Weishampel,  D.B.,  Dodson,  P., Osmo \u0301lska, H.  (Eds.), The Dinosauria, University of California Press, Berkeley, pp. 345\u2013401.</ref> along with the also controversial genus [[Zizhongosaurus]], but that was based more on the geological age of the two sauropods ([[Toarcian]]) than on a comparative study of the morphology between the genera.<ref name=\"Upchurch, P. 1995\"/> The clade Vulcanodontidae later became a waste-basket taxon for many unrelated basal sauropods. ''Ohmdenosaurus'' has not been confirmed by an exact analysis as a \"Vulcanodontid\" in the modern sense, neither a relative of [[Vulcanodon]]. The latest studies had been suggested that ''Ohmdenosaurus'' is a more basal [[gravisauria]]n, closely related to the Australian genus ''[[Rhoetosaurus]]''. The reassignation of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' was proposed due to similarities such as the presence of a proximal and distal surfaces of the astragalus, or the presence of a rounded cnemial crest nearly identical on ''[[Rhoetosaurus]]''. Astragalus morphology is also present on [[Ferganasaurus]], but in overall morphology, ''Ohmdenosaurus'' is considered the closest genera.<ref>Nair, J. P., & Salisbury, S. W. (2012). New anatomical information on Rhoetosaurus brownei Longman, 1926, a gravisaurian sauropodomorph dinosaur from the Middle Jurassic of Queensland, Australia. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 32(2), 369\u2013394.</ref> That was also recovered in 2015, with the find of new Gravisaurian remains from the Toarcian of Northern Germany, possibly distinct from ''Ohmdenosaurus'' as they bear more similarity to ''[[Tazoudasaurus]]'' than ''Rhoetosaurus''.<ref>Stumpf, S., Ansorge, J., & Krempien, W. (2015). Gravisaurian sauropod remains from the marine late Early Jurassic (Lower Toarcian) of North-Eastern Germany. Geobios, 48(3), 271\u2013279.</ref>\n\n== Paleoenvironment ==\n[[File:Ohmdenosaurus Reconstruction.jpg|thumb|320px|left|Restoration of 2 specimens on a Podocarpaceae forest]]\nBased on the paleogeography of the fossils, the early Jurassic sauropods occur more in middle latitudes, with a probably Tethyan distribution, rather than at higher latitudes.<ref>Gillette, D. D. (2003). The geographic and phylogenetic position of sauropod dinosaurs from the Kota formation (Early Jurassic) of India. Journal of Asian Earth Sciences, 21(6), 683\u2013689.</ref> ''Ohmdenosaurus'' is one of the few body fossil sauropod remains found in Europe. During the [[Toarcian]] the [[Posidonia Shale]] extended along a mostly marine Basin, with the main Terrestrial environments of the Posidonia Shale being the near emerged lands, mostly of Paleozoic Origin such as [[London-Brabant Massif]] at the west, the French [[Central Massif]] at the south, the [[Vindelician High]] and [[Bohemian Massif]] at the east, with minor lands present whose emerged nature on the Toarcian is controversial, including the [[Vlotho Massif]] at the northwest, the Swedish [[Bern]] high at the south, [[Rhenish Massif]] on the Center and the [[Fuenen High]] in the north.<ref>L\u00e9zin, C., Andreu, B., Pellenard, P., Bouchez, J. L., Emmanuel, L., Faur\u00e9, P., & Landrein, P. (2013). Geochemical disturbance and paleoenvironmental changes during the Early Toarcian in NW Europe. Chemical Geology, 341, 1\u201315.</ref> The Bones of Ohmdenosaurus are believed to have come from the [[Vindelician High]] or the [[Bohemian Massif]] (Connected). The landmass had an extension similar to modern [[Ireland]], with an island environment, part of the coast called [[Vindelician Land]], composed of large seashore environments, including [[River Delta]]s, [[Mangrove]]s, [[Lagoon]]s, Brackish deposits and other similar. The strata of the nearshore environments are populated by charcoal, which suggests a wide presence of fires.<ref>AMMON VON L. 1875. Die Jura Ablagerungen zwischen Regensburg und Passau. Theodor Ackermann, M\u00fcnchen</ref> The terrestrial environments where populated by a large variety of flora, including [[Equisetaceae]], [[Osmundaceae]], [[Umkomasiaceae]], [[Bennettitales]], [[Araucariaceae]], [[Cupressaceae]] and [[Podocarpaceae]].<ref name=\"Wilde55\">Wilde, V. (2001). Die Landpflanzen-Taphoz\u00f6nose aus dem Posidonienschiefer des Unteren Jura (Schwarzer Jura [Epsilon], Unter-Toarcium) in Deutschland und ihre Deutung. Staatliches Museum f\u00fcr Naturkunde.</ref><ref>Prauss, M., Ligouis, B., & Luterbacher, H. (1991). Organic matter and palynomorphs in the \u2018Posidonienschiefer\u2019(Toarcian, Lower Jurassic) of southern Germany. Geological Society, London, Special Publications, 58(1), 335\u2013351.</ref> The fauna was composed mostly by Insects, with a high variety of genera.<ref>Ansorge, J. (2003). Insects from the Lower Toarcian of middle Europe and England. Acta zoologica cracoviensia, 46(SUPPL.), 291-310.</ref> The only other vertebrates to be found related to semiterrestrial settings are Pterosaurs, especially [[Campylognathoides]], considered an inland insect hunter, or the more marine [[Dorygnathus]]. [[Testudinata]]ns were reported on the 1800s,<ref>M\u00dcNSTER, G.G. ZU. 1834. Mittheilung, an Professor Bronn gerichtet. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde 1834:42\u201343</ref> although now are lost.<ref>Joyce, W. G. (2017). A review of the fossil record of basal Mesozoic turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History, 58(1), 65-113</ref> The other seashore related animals can be the marine [[Teleosauridae]], such as [[Platysuchus]] or the marine sphenodont [[Palaeopleurosaurus]]. A possible  [[Trithelodontidae|Trithelodontid]](?) cynodont was cited on 1800s papers, but its presence has not been proved.<ref>M\u00dcNSTER, G. (1836). Letter on various fossils. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde, 1836, 580-583</ref> The Environments were influenced by monsoonal conditions, and large scale rains that hit most of the nearshore settings, causing the large accumulation of Insect remains found on the epicontinental layers. Southern summers with humid south-west monsoonal conditions occur on most of the emerged lands, getting a winter with dry north east trade winds. Those were related to the seasonal occurrence of wood rafts on the formation and linked to the life cycle of the stem crinoids. On the land, probably where the main source of seeds and help to interchange species between landmasses.<ref>R\u00f6hl, H. J., Schmid-R\u00f6hl, A., Oschmann, W., Frimmel, A., & Schwark, L. (2001). The Posidonia Shale (Lower Toarcian) of SW-Germany: an oxygen-depleted ecosystem controlled by sea level and palaeoclimate. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology, 165(1\u20132), 27\u201352.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"wild1978\">{{cite journal|last=Wild |first=R. |year=1978 |title=Ein Sauropoden-Rest (Reptilia, Saurischia) aus dem Posidonienschiefer (Lias, Toarcium) von Holzmaden |language=German| journal=Stuttgarter Beitr\u00e4ge zur Naturkunde, Serie B (Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie) |volume=41 |pages=1\u201315}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n{{Sauropodomorpha|B.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q311380}}\n\n[[Category:Sauropods]]\n[[Category:Early Jurassic dinosaurs of Europe]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Germany]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Germany]]\n[[Category:Posidonia Shale]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1978]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|fossil_range = [[Toarcian]], {{fossil range|180}}\n|image =Ohmdenosaurus.JPG\n|image_caption = Fossil tibia and astragalus\n|genus = Ohmdenosaurus\n|species = liasicus\n|authority = Wild, 1978\n}}\n\n'''''Ohmdenosaurus''''' (meaning \"Ohmden lizard\") is a [[genus]] of [[herbivorous]] [[dinosaur]] from the Lower or middle [[Toarcian]] stage of the Early [[Jurassic]] from what is now [[Ohmden]], [[Germany]]. It is one of the earliest representatives of the [[Sauropoda|sauropods]] group of [[Europe]], with dubious representatives known by footprints from the [[Sinemurian]] of [[Romania]],<ref>G. Pienkowski, M. E. Popa, and A. Kedzior. 2009. Early Jurassic sauropod footprints of the Southern Carpathians, Romania: palaeobiological and palaeogeographical significance. Geological Quarterly 53(4):461-470</ref> [[Poland]]<ref>G. Gierlinski. 1991. New dinosaur ichnotaxa from the Early Jurassic of the Holy Cross Mountains, Poland. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology 85:137-148</ref> or [[Italy]],<ref>M. Avanzini and G. Leonardi. 1993. Dinosauri nel Trentino: il giacimento dei Lavini di Marco [Dinosaurs in Trentino: the locality of Lavini di Marco]. UCT (Uomo - Citt\u00e0 - Territorio) 214:35-41</ref> bing an excepcional discovery, since late Liassic dinosaurs tend to be a rare thing, especially  in Europe. It is also currently one of the few [[Sauropoda|sauropods]] described from the [[Toarcian]] of the modern northern hemisphere, along with ''[[Tazoudasaurus]]'' which has been considered a relative. ''Ohmdenosaurus'' lived on an island series in what is now the region of [[Bohemia]]. It was mistaken originally as a plesiosaur remains, until a revision of the holotype in 1978. It is the only dinosaur identified from the [[Posidonia Shale]].<ref name=\"wild1978\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Ohmdenosaurus Scale.svg|thumb|300px|left|Scaled type specimen]] \n''Ohmdenosaurus'' is considered a primitive sauropod, although not the most known one. Following the Sauropod morphological trend, it is believed that it's appearance would be that of a fully cuadrupedal animal, with a long neck and a relative robust body. Is not really known the range of specialization of primitive sauropods referred to its diet, being hervivorous, but probably with different choices concerning the type of vegetation. ''Ohmdenosaurus'' probably ranged from medium to high vegetation, with plants like tall [[Bennettitales]], [[Araucariaceae]] and [[Podocarpaceae]] trees being among the most probably components of its diet.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The type specimen of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' consists on a [[Tibia]] and a [[Talus bone]] (Astragalus). The Tibia possesses a bent and sloping, powerful [[Cnemial Crest]], that is delimited laterally by a sulcus; it has a  the proximal joint end,  perpendicular to the longitudinal axis of the shaft; the lateral part of the tibia has a lateral crista that extends to the middle; The Astragalus is flat in comparison to the Tibia, with a sandal-shaped form, without ascending process; calcaneus has small proportions, and is disc-shaped.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The articulation presents a possible joint with bony sesamoids, but that wasn't compared.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The size of the Tibia is 405&nbsp;mm long according to Wild<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> and Carrano (1998),<ref>Carrano, M. T. (1998). The evolution of dinosaur locomotion: biomechanics, functional morphology, and modern analogs (Doctoral dissertation, Ph. D. thesis. University of Chicago, Chicago, Ill).</ref> with an estimated femur length of at least 70&nbsp;cm. This yielded traditionally an estimated total body length of {{Convert|4|m|ft|abbr=on}}. This is relatively small for a sauropod.<ref name=\"wild1978\" /><ref name=\"Upchurch, P. 1995\">Upchurch, P. (1995). The evolutionary history of sauropod dinosaurs. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B: Biological Sciences, 349(1330), 365-390.</ref> The small size of ''Ohmdenosaurus''led to speculate that the taxon may have been one of the few examples on insular dwarfism on Sauropods, being a similar case to that of the also German [[Late Jurassic]] Macronarian [[Europasaurus]]. That was recovered on several books and studies, altrougth it hasn't been proved.<ref>Gro\u00dfmann, F. (2006). Taxonomy, Phylogeny and Palaeoecology of the Plesiosauroids (sauropterygia, Reptilia) from the Posidonia Shale (Toarcian, Lower Jurassic) of Holzmaden, South West Germany: Dissertation Zur Erlangung Des Grades Eines Doktors Der Naturwissenschaften (p. 135). Geowissenschaftlichen Fakult\u00e4t der Eberhard-Karls-Universit\u00e4t.</ref>''Ohmdenosaurus'' has been suggested as a juvenile individual on several encyclopedias, altrought there hasn't done any osteological study to prove it.<ref>Mclntosh, J. S. (1997). M. K. Brett-Surman, and James O. Farlow. The Complete Dinosaur, 264.</ref><ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{Cite book | last1 = Holtz | first1 = Thomas R., Jr. | last2 = Rey | first2 = Luis V. | title = Dinosaurs: the most complete, up-to-date encyclopedia for dinosaur lovers of all ages | url = https://archive.org/details/dinosaursmostcom00holt | year = 2007 | publisher = Random House | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-375-82419-7 | access-date = 2012-01-26 | url-status = live }}</ref> Molina P\u00e9rez & Larramendi, stated that the sauropod was \"downgraded\" in size, with an unexplained reduction when a femur of 70&nbsp;cm is suggested. They suggested a new size of 6.7 m long, with a weight of 1.3 tonnes. The last stimation however, should be taken with caution, as the specimen would need a \"in depth\" revision, as is based on a not concretely stimated tibia.<ref>Molina-P\u00e9rez, R., & Larramendi, A. (2020). Dinosaur Facts and Figures: The Sauropods and Other Sauropodomorphs. Princeton University Press.</ref>\n\n==History of discovery==\nIn the 1970s, German [[palaeontologist]] Rupert Wild, visiting the [[Urwelt-Museum Hauff]] at [[Holzmaden]] in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], noticed a fossil in a display labelled as an [[humerus|upper arm bone]] of a [[plesiosaur]] which he recognized as a misidentified dinosaur fossil.<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> The bone had been collected from one of the early quarries near [[Ohmden]] that was later refilled. Although the exact discovery site is unknown, rock attached to the lower end of the fossil comes from the ''unterer Schiefer'' (\"lower slate\"), the oldest part of the [[Posidonia Shale]].<ref name=\"wild1978\"/> It is therefore Early [[Toarcian]] in age (182.0 to 175.6 mya).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicTaxonInfo?taxon_no=65914|publisher=[[Paleobiology Database]]|website=paleobiodb.org|access-date=2019-08-04|title=''Ohmdenosaurus liasicus'' Wild 1978 (sauropod)}}</ref>\nFurther study determined that the fossil belonged to a new genus and species of early sauropod, which Wild named ''Ohmdenosaurus liasicus'' in a 1978 publication. The fossil, which lacks an inventory number, consists of a right [[tibia]] (shinbone) together with the upper bones of the ankle, the [[Talus bone|astragalus]] and the [[calcaneus]]. The bones, disarticulated in the fossil, show signs of weathering, evidence that the animal died on land and that only later were its bones washed into the sea.\n\n== Classification ==\nThe shape of the astragalus - which is not convex on top as it is in derived members of [[Neosauropoda]] - suggests that ''Ohmdenosaurus'' was a very basal sauropod, altrought with the finds on new groups such as [[Lessemsauridae]] the status of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' has slightly changed, being seen as a less basal taxon, related on mostly of the contemporaneous works to the [[Gravisauria]]ns. In 1990 John Stanton McIntosh included ''Ohmdenosaurus'' in the [[Vulcanodontidae]]<ref>McIntosh,  J.S.,  1990.  Sauropoda.  In:  Weishampel,  D.B.,  Dodson,  P.,Osmo \u0301lska, H.  (Eds.), The Dinosauria, University of California Press,Berkeley, pp. 345 \u2013 401.</ref> along with the also controversial genus [[Zizhongosaurus]], but that was based more on the geological age of the two sauropods ([[Toarcian]]) than on a comparative study of the morphology between the genera.<ref name=\"Upchurch, P. 1995\"/> The clade Vulcanodontidae later became a waste-basket taxon for many unrelated basal sauropods. ''Ohmdenosaurus'' has not been confirmed by an exact analysis as a \"Vulcanodontid\" in the modern sense, neither a relative of [[Vulcanodon]]. The latest studies had been suggested that ''Ohmdenosaurus'' is a more basal [[gravisauria]]n, closely related to the Australian genus ''[[Rhoetosaurus]]''. The reasignation of ''Ohmdenosaurus'' was proposed due to similarities such as the presence of a proximal and distal surfaces of the astragalus, or the presence of a rounded cnemial crest nearly identical on ''[[Rhoetosaurus]]''. Astragalus morphology is also present on [[Ferganasaurus]], but in overall morphology, ''Ohmdenosaurus'' is considered the closest genera.<ref>Nair, J. P., & Salisbury, S. W. (2012). New anatomical information on Rhoetosaurus brownei Longman, 1926, a gravisaurian sauropodomorph dinosaur from the Middle Jurassic of Queensland, Australia. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 32(2), 369-394.</ref> That was also recovered in 2015, with the find of new Gravisaurian remains from the Toarcian of Northern Germany, possibly distinct from ''Ohmdenosaurus'' as they bear more similarity to ''[[Tazoudasaurus]]'' than ''Rhoetosaurus''.<ref>Stumpf, S., Ansorge, J., & Krempien, W. (2015). Gravisaurian sauropod remains from the marine late Early Jurassic (Lower Toarcian) of North-Eastern Germany. Geobios, 48(3), 271-279.</ref>\n\n== Paleoenvironment ==\n[[File:Ohmdenosaurus Reconstruction.jpg|thumb|320px|left|Restoration of 2 specimens on a Podocarpaceae forest]]\nBased on the paleogeography of the fossils, the early Jurassic sauropods occur more in middle latitudes, with a probably Tethyan distribution, rather than at higher latitudes.<ref>Gillette, D. D. (2003). The geographic and phylogenetic position of sauropod dinosaurs from the Kota formation (Early Jurassic) of India. Journal of Asian Earth Sciences, 21(6), 683-689.</ref> ''Ohmdenosaurus'' is one of the few body fossil sauropod remains found on Europe. During the [[Toarcian]] the [[Posidonia Shale]] extended along a mostly marine Basin, with the main Terrestrial environments of the Posidonia Shale being the near emerged lands, mostly of Paleozoic Origin such as [[London-Brabant Massif]] at the west, the French [[Central Massif]] at the south, the [[Vindelician High]] and [[Bohemian Massif]] at the east, with minor lands present whose emerged nature on the Toarcian is controversial, including the [[Vlotho Massif]] at the northwest, the Swedish [[Bern]] high at the south, [[Rhenish Massif]] on the Center and the [[Fuenen High]] in the north.<ref>L\u00e9zin, C., Andreu, B., Pellenard, P., Bouchez, J. L., Emmanuel, L., Faur\u00e9, P., & Landrein, P. (2013). Geochemical disturbance and paleoenvironmental changes during the Early Toarcian in NW Europe. Chemical Geology, 341, 1\u201315.</ref> The Bones of Ohmdenosaurus are believed to have come from the [[Vindelician High]] or the [[Bohemian Massif]] (Connected). The lansmass had an extension similar to modern [[Ireland]], with an island environment, part of the coast called [[Vindelician Land]], composed of large seashore environments, including [[River Delta]]s, [[Mangrove]]s, [[Lagoon]]s, Brackish deposits and other similar. The strata of the nearshore environments are populated by Charcoal, what suggest a wide presence of fires.<ref>AMMON VON L. 1875. Die Jura Ablagerungen zwischen Regensburg und Passau. Theodor Ackermann, M\u00fcnchen</ref> The terrestrial environments where populated by a large variety of flora, including [[Equisetaceae]], [[Osmundaceae]], [[Umkomasiaceae]], [[Bennettitales]], [[Araucariaceae]], [[Cupressaceae]] and [[Podocarpaceae]].<ref name=\"Wilde55\">Wilde, V. (2001). Die Landpflanzen-Taphoz\u00f6nose aus dem Posidonienschiefer des Unteren Jura (Schwarzer Jura [Epsilon], Unter-Toarcium) in Deutschland und ihre Deutung. Staatliches Museum f\u00fcr Naturkunde.</ref><ref>Prauss, M., Ligouis, B., & Luterbacher, H. (1991). Organic matter and palynomorphs in the \u2018Posidonienschiefer\u2019(Toarcian, Lower Jurassic) of southern Germany. Geological Society, London, Special Publications, 58(1), 335\u2013351.</ref> The fauna was composed mostly by Insects, with a high variety of genera.<ref>Ansorge, J. (2003). Insects from the lower Toarcian of middle Europe and England. Acta zoologica cracoviensia, 46(SUPPL.), 291-310.</ref> The only other vertebrates to be found related to semiterrestrial settings are Pterosaurs, specially [[Campylognathoides]], considered an inland insect hunter, or the more marine [[Dorygnathus]]. [[Testudinata]]ns where reported on the 1800s,<ref>M\u00dcNSTER, G.G. ZU. 1834. Mittheilung, an Professor Bronn gerichtet. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde 1834:42\u201343</ref> altrougth now are lost.<ref>Joyce, W. G. (2017). A review of the fossil record of basal Mesozoic turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History, 58(1), 65-113</ref> The other seashore related animals can be the marine [[Teleosauridae]], such as [[Platysuchus]] or the marine sphenodont [[Palaeopleurosaurus]]. A possible  [[Trithelodontidae|Trithelodontid]](?) cynodont was cited on 1800s papers, but its presence has not been proved.<ref>M\u00dcNSTER, G. (1836). Letter on various fossils. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde, 1836, 580-583</ref> The Environments were influenced by monsoonal conditions, and large scale rains that hit most of the nearshore settings, causing the large accumulation of Insect remains found on the epicontinental layers. Southern summers with humid south-west monsoonal conditions occur on most of the emerged lands, getting a winter with dry north east trade winds. Those were related to the seasonal occurrence of wood rafts on the formation and linked to the life cycle of the stem crinoids. On the land, probably where the main source of seeds and help to interchange species between landmasses.<ref>R\u00f6hl, H. J., Schmid-R\u00f6hl, A., Oschmann, W., Frimmel, A., & Schwark, L. (2001). The Posidonia Shale (Lower Toarcian) of SW-Germany: an oxygen-depleted ecosystem controlled by sea level and palaeoclimate. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology, 165(1-2), 27\u201352.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"wild1978\">{{cite journal|last=Wild |first=R. |year=1978 |title=Ein Sauropoden-Rest (Reptilia, Saurischia) aus dem Posidonienschiefer (Lias, Toarcium) von Holzmaden |language=German| journal=Stuttgarter Beitr\u00e4ge zur Naturkunde, Serie B (Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie) |volume=41 |pages=1\u201315}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n{{Sauropodomorpha|B.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q311380}}\n\n[[Category:Sauropods]]\n[[Category:Early Jurassic dinosaurs of Europe]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Germany]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Germany]]\n[[Category:Posidonia Shale]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1978]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "it's \u2192 its; copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohmdenosaurus"}
{"title_page": "Dustin Hodge", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dustin Hodge\n| image              = Dustin Hodge.jpg\n| caption            = Hodge in January 2019\n| birth_place        = [[Stephenville, Texas]], U.S.\n| education          = [[Arizona State University]] <br> [[Goucher College]]\n| occupation         = [[Television producer]], [[Screenwriter]]\n| website            = {{url|https://dustinhodge.com}}\n| years_active       = 2003\u2013present\n|| spouse             = {{marriage|Donna Hodge|2013|}}\n}}\n\n'''Dustin Hodge''' is an American television writer and producer. He is the founder of Hodge Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustinhodge|title=Dustin Hodge {{!}} Hodge Media Group|website=hodgeproductions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>, a Colorado media company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5635005/tv-series-little-britches-rodeo-to-film-in-oklahoma/|title=TV series 'Little Britches Rodeo' to film in Oklahoma|date=2019-06-27|website=Oklahoman.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>He is known for working on a variety of nonfiction content. His most notable work is as the showrunner for [[Little Britches Rodeo (TV series)]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nHodge was born in [[Stephenville, Texas]] and graduated high school from [[Dublin, Texas]]. Hodge graduated ''summa cum laude'' from [[Arizona State University]] in Communications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1823566/bio|title=Dustin Hodge|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> Hodge is married to Donna Hodge, Ph.D., the Chief Strategy Officer at Colorado State University Pueblo in Pueblo, Colorado.\n\n== Career ==\n\nHodge began his film career working on commercials, music videos, and short videos in Dallas, Texas.<ref name=\"story\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourstephenvilletx.com/news/20181125/storyteller-erath-native-exploring-expanse-of-possibilities-in-film-world|title=Storyteller: Erath native exploring 'expanse of possibilities' in film world|last=Wilsonmwilson@empiretribune.com|first=Mark|website=Stephenville Empire-Tribune|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> He later worked as a production assistant on series like [[Prison Break]]<ref name=\"story\" /> and as a camera operator on shows like [[Cheaters]] and an [[Eye for an Eye]] and feature films like [[Bollywood Beats]]. He was the cinematographer for the feature film Diwali.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archives.etypeservices.com/Dublin1/Magazine58491/Publication/Magazine58491.pdf#page=3|title=Where Are They Now|last=Frederick|first=Eva|date=2014-07-17|work=The Dublin Citizen|access-date=}}</ref> Later he worked as a producer on televised sports programming like [[Champs Boxing]], Wrecking Ball Wrestling, and [[Art of War 3]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/381c30_30cb502ee1934d9f8e421ffd5d282949.pdf|title=Hodge Studio|last=Stevens|first=Siri|date=2013-12-08|work=Rodeo News|access-date=}}</ref> He was a reoccurring morning guest and wrote content for [[KWTX-FM]]. Hodge has also worked as a photojournalist and documentarian across most of Western Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustinhodge|title=Dustin Hodge {{!}} Hodge Media Group|website=hodgeproductions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nLater he worked for the CBS-affiliate [[KKTV]], in Colorado Springs, CO as a news producer and journalist. He was part of the production team that covered the [[Waldo Canyon fire]] in Colorado for 130 continuous hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csindy.com/coloradosprings/best-of-2012-personalities/BestOf?oid=2577380|title=Best of 2012: Personalities|last=staff|first=Indy|website=Colorado Springs Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nHodge is the show-runner for the national television series [[Little Britches Rodeo (TV series)|Little Britches Rodeo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/entertainment/20181204/puebloan-dustin-hodges-rodeo-based-tv-series-in-its-seventh-year|title=Puebloan Dustin Hodge's rodeo-based TV series in its seventh year|last=Pompia|first=John|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/news/20200225/pueblo-commission-working-to-recruit-film-industry|title=Pueblo commission working to recruit film industry|last=Chieftain|first=Jon Pompia The Pueblo|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>and has written and produced 208 episodes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://static.wixstatic.com/ugd/381c30_de979aed3b744dcaa01b527db62510e7.pdf|title=DHS grad helms national rodeo show|last=Gaudette|first=Paul|date=2019-07-11|work=The Dublin Citizen|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Little Britches Rodeo|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3132420/|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>  In addition, he is the show-runner for the series, [[Little Britches on the Road]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guthrienewsleader.net/news/national-little-britches-rodeo-tv-series-to-air-this-fall/article_dbed1e6a-9db1-11e9-9900-a3f7e204e6c5.html|title=National Little Britches Rodeo TV Series to air this fall|last=Ediger|first=Karan|website=Guthrie News Leader|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> Both series air in more than 52 million homes on [[RFD-TV]] and are syndicated in another 42 million homes on the [[The Cowboy Channel]].\n\nHodge has produced dozens of short documentaries covering programing by [[El Pueblo History Museum]], [[History Colorado]], and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. He was also the producer for the feature documentaries [[The Arkansas River: From Leadville to Lamar]] and Tha Bridge, a documentary about hip-hop.\n\nHodge regularly speaks and presents about topics in media, pop culture, rural issues, and literacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libraryvision.org/colorado_dialogue_on_public_libraries|title=Colorado Dialogue on Public Libraries|website=The Aspen Institute Dialogue on Public Libraries|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arts.gov/art-works/2018/falling-love-new-books-neabigread|title=Falling in Love with New Books for the #NEABigRead|date=2018-10-22|website=NEA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/pueblowestview/ff668fef-77c3-5ebd-ba2e-95e37e8b1bdc.html|title=Friends of the Library award|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/pueblowestview/11f58a89-b20f-509d-a5af-6d71f9bbe0d2.html|title=Film fest a testament to tenacity|last=jpompia@chieftain.com|first=Jon Pompia The Pueblo Chieftain|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustin|title=Dustin Hodge {{!}} Hodge Media Group|website=hodgeproductions|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film and television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Note\n! colspan=\"4\" |Credited as\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |Director\n! width=\"65\" |Producer\n! width=\"65\" |Writer\n|-\n|2013\u2013Present\n|[[Little Britches Rodeo (TV series)|Little Britches Rodeo]]\n|TV Series\n|182 Episodes\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2013-2017\n|[[Little Britches on the Road]]\n|TV Series\n|17 Episodes\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2008\n|Wrecking Ball Wrestling 3\n|TV - Sports\n|Wrestling\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2008\n|Wrecking Ball Wrestling 2\n|TV - Sports\n|Wrestling\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2008\n|Wrecking Ball Wrestling 1\n|TV - Sports\n|Wrestling\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2007\n|[[Art of War 3]]\n|TV - Sports\n|Mixed Martial Arts\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2003\n|[[Champs Boxing]]\n|TV Series\n|4 Episodes\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Documentaries===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Note\n! colspan=\"4\" |Credited as\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |Director\n! width=\"65\" |Producer\n! width=\"65\" |Writer\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Tha Bridge]]\n|Documentary\n|\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[[The Arkansas River: From Leadville to Lamar]]\n|Documentary\n|\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Documentary (Short Subject)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Note\n! colspan=\"4\" |Credited as\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |Director\n! width=\"65\" |Producer\n! width=\"65\" |Writer\n|-\n|2018\n|Oral Histories of Southern Colorado\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Alternative Energy: Clean Initiatives\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Healthcare in Rural America\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Hands-on History for Schools\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2015\n|Shorty Koger: Western History\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2015\n|Literary Landmarks: The Mediterranean\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2014\n|Literary Landmarks: Twain's Tramps Abroad\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2013\n|Literary Landmarks: The British Isles\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2012\n|Literary Landmarks: Language, Literature, and the Art of Study Abroad\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2011\n|From Pueblo to Pompeii\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|1823566}}\n* [https://www.dustinhodge.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustinhodge Profile on production page]\n\n[[Category:American documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Colorado]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Showrunners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodge, Dustin}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dustin Hodge\n| image              = Dustin Hodge.jpg\n| caption            = Hodge in January 2019\n| birth_place        = [[Stephenville, Texas]], U.S.\n| education          = [[Arizona State University]] <br> [[Goucher College]]\n| occupation         = [[Television producer]], [[Screenwriter]]\n| website            = {{url|https://dustinhodge.com}}\n| years_active       = 2003\u2013present\n|| spouse             = {{marriage|Donna Hodge|2013|}}\n}}\n\n'''Dustin Hodge''' is an American television writer and producer. He is the founder of Hodge Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustinhodge|title=Dustin Hodge {{!}} Hodge Media Group|website=hodgeproductions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>, a Colorado media company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5635005/tv-series-little-britches-rodeo-to-film-in-oklahoma/|title=TV series 'Little Britches Rodeo' to film in Oklahoma|date=2019-06-27|website=Oklahoman.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>He is know for working on a variety of nonfiction content. His most notable work is as the showrunner for [[Little Britches Rodeo (TV series)]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nHodge was born in [[Stephenville, Texas]] and graduated high school from [[Dublin, Texas]]. Hodge graduated ''summa cum laude'' from [[Arizona State University]] in Communications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1823566/bio|title=Dustin Hodge|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> Hodge is married to Donna Hodge, Ph.D., the Chief Strategy Officer at Colorado State University Pueblo in Pueblo, Colorado.\n\n== Career ==\n\nHodge began his film career working on commercials, music videos, and short videos in Dallas, Texas.<ref name=\"story\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourstephenvilletx.com/news/20181125/storyteller-erath-native-exploring-expanse-of-possibilities-in-film-world|title=Storyteller: Erath native exploring 'expanse of possibilities' in film world|last=Wilsonmwilson@empiretribune.com|first=Mark|website=Stephenville Empire-Tribune|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> He later worked as a production assistant on series like [[Prison Break]]<ref name=\"story\" /> and as a camera operator on shows like [[Cheaters]] and an [[Eye for an Eye]] and feature films like [[Bollywood Beats]]. He was the cinematographer for the feature film Diwali.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archives.etypeservices.com/Dublin1/Magazine58491/Publication/Magazine58491.pdf#page=3|title=Where Are They Now|last=Frederick|first=Eva|date=2014-07-17|work=The Dublin Citizen|access-date=}}</ref> Later he worked as a producer on televised sports programming like [[Champs Boxing]], Wrecking Ball Wrestling, and [[Art of War 3]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/381c30_30cb502ee1934d9f8e421ffd5d282949.pdf|title=Hodge Studio|last=Stevens|first=Siri|date=2013-12-08|work=Rodeo News|access-date=}}</ref> He was a reoccurring morning guest and wrote content for [[KWTX-FM]]. Hodge has also worked as a photojournalist and documentarian across most of Western Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustinhodge|title=Dustin Hodge {{!}} Hodge Media Group|website=hodgeproductions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nLater he worked for the CBS-affiliate [[KKTV]], in Colorado Springs, CO as a news producer and journalist. He was part of the production team that covered the [[Waldo Canyon fire]] in Colorado for 130 continuous hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csindy.com/coloradosprings/best-of-2012-personalities/BestOf?oid=2577380|title=Best of 2012: Personalities|last=staff|first=Indy|website=Colorado Springs Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nHodge is the show-runner for the national television series [[Little Britches Rodeo (TV series)|Little Britches Rodeo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/entertainment/20181204/puebloan-dustin-hodges-rodeo-based-tv-series-in-its-seventh-year|title=Puebloan Dustin Hodge's rodeo-based TV series in its seventh year|last=Pompia|first=John|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/news/20200225/pueblo-commission-working-to-recruit-film-industry|title=Pueblo commission working to recruit film industry|last=Chieftain|first=Jon Pompia The Pueblo|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>and has written and produced 208 episodes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://static.wixstatic.com/ugd/381c30_de979aed3b744dcaa01b527db62510e7.pdf|title=DHS grad helms national rodeo show|last=Gaudette|first=Paul|date=2019-07-11|work=The Dublin Citizen|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Little Britches Rodeo|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3132420/|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>  In addition, he is the show-runner for the series, [[Little Britches on the Road]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guthrienewsleader.net/news/national-little-britches-rodeo-tv-series-to-air-this-fall/article_dbed1e6a-9db1-11e9-9900-a3f7e204e6c5.html|title=National Little Britches Rodeo TV Series to air this fall|last=Ediger|first=Karan|website=Guthrie News Leader|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> Both series air in more than 52 million homes on [[RFD-TV]] and are syndicated in another 42 million homes on the [[The Cowboy Channel]].\n\nHodge has produced dozens of short documentaries covering programing by [[El Pueblo History Museum]], [[History Colorado]], and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. He was also the producer for the feature documentaries [[The Arkansas River: From Leadville to Lamar]] and Tha Bridge, a documentary about hip-hop.\n\nHodge regularly speaks and presents about topics in media, pop culture, rural issues, and literacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.libraryvision.org/colorado_dialogue_on_public_libraries|title=Colorado Dialogue on Public Libraries|website=The Aspen Institute Dialogue on Public Libraries|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arts.gov/art-works/2018/falling-love-new-books-neabigread|title=Falling in Love with New Books for the #NEABigRead|date=2018-10-22|website=NEA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/pueblowestview/ff668fef-77c3-5ebd-ba2e-95e37e8b1bdc.html|title=Friends of the Library award|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chieftain.com/pueblowestview/11f58a89-b20f-509d-a5af-6d71f9bbe0d2.html|title=Film fest a testament to tenacity|last=jpompia@chieftain.com|first=Jon Pompia The Pueblo Chieftain|website=The Pueblo Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodgemediagroup.com/dustin|title=Dustin Hodge {{!}} Hodge Media Group|website=hodgeproductions|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film and television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Note\n! colspan=\"4\" |Credited as\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |Director\n! width=\"65\" |Producer\n! width=\"65\" |Writer\n|-\n|2013\u2013Present\n|[[Little Britches Rodeo (TV series)|Little Britches Rodeo]]\n|TV Series\n|182 Episodes\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2013-2017\n|[[Little Britches on the Road]]\n|TV Series\n|17 Episodes\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2008\n|Wrecking Ball Wrestling 3\n|TV - Sports\n|Wrestling\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2008\n|Wrecking Ball Wrestling 2\n|TV - Sports\n|Wrestling\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2008\n|Wrecking Ball Wrestling 1\n|TV - Sports\n|Wrestling\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2007\n|[[Art of War 3]]\n|TV - Sports\n|Mixed Martial Arts\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2003\n|[[Champs Boxing]]\n|TV Series\n|4 Episodes\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Documentaries===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Note\n! colspan=\"4\" |Credited as\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |Director\n! width=\"65\" |Producer\n! width=\"65\" |Writer\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Tha Bridge]]\n|Documentary\n|\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[[The Arkansas River: From Leadville to Lamar]]\n|Documentary\n|\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Documentary (Short Subject)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Note\n! colspan=\"4\" |Credited as\n|-\n! width=\"65\" |Director\n! width=\"65\" |Producer\n! width=\"65\" |Writer\n|-\n|2018\n|Oral Histories of Southern Colorado\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Alternative Energy: Clean Initiatives\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Healthcare in Rural America\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Hands-on History for Schools\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2015\n|Shorty Koger: Western History\n|Short\n|Documentary\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2015\n|Literary Landmarks: The Mediterranean\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2014\n|Literary Landmarks: Twain's Tramps Abroad\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2013\n|Literary Landmarks: The British Isles\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2012\n|Literary Landmarks: Language, Literature, and the Art of Study Abroad\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n|2011\n|From Pueblo to Pompeii\n|Short\n|Travel\n| {{yes}}\n| {{y