{"title_page": "Arturo Sandoval", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban jazz trumpeter, pianist and composer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Arturo Sandoval\n| image            = Arturo Sandoval photo.jpg\n| caption          = Sandoval performing in 2008\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = 6 November 1949 (Age 70)\n| birth_place      = [[Artemisa]], Cuba\n| genre            = [[Jazz]], [[Latin Jazz]], [[Afro-Cuban]]\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Trumpet, Piano, Timbales\n| years_active     = 1977\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = [[Irakere]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[GRP All-Star Big Band]]\n| website          = {{URL|arturosandoval.com}}\n}}\n'''Arturo Sandoval''' is a [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]] [[jazz]] trumpeter, pianist and composer.\n\nSandoval, while living in his native [[Cuba]], was influenced by jazz musicians [[Charlie Parker]], [[Clifford Brown]], and [[Dizzy Gillespie]], finally meeting Gillespie later in 1977. Gillespie became a mentor and colleague, playing with Sandoval in concerts in Europe and Cuba and later featuring him in the United Nations Orchestra. Sandoval defected while touring with Gillespie in 1990, and he became an American [[naturalized citizen]] in 1998.\n\nHis life was the subject of the film ''[[For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story]]'' (2000), starring [[Andy Garc\u00eda]]. Sandoval has won ten [[Grammy Awards]] and been nominated nineteen times; he has also received six [[Billboard Awards|''Billboard'' Awards]] and one [[Emmy Award]]. Additionally, Sandoval has performed in a [[List of Super Bowl halftime shows|Super Bowl Halftime Show]] (1995),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-04-23-ca-51420-story.html|title=Trumpeter Arturo Sandoval Is Denied U.S. Citizenship|author=Clary, Mike|date=April 23, 1997|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> in an [[Orange Bowl]] (2009)<ref>{{Citation|last=SMS PTY|title=Arturo Sandoval Orange Bowl 2009|date=January 1, 2009|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G_Q1zNstmSY|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> at the [[White House]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/11/28/castro-critic-was-playing-scullers-when-learned-former-cuban-leader-death/N2vTTtsG08gaK10v9AOlGP/story.html|title=A Castro critic was playing Scullers when he learned of the former Cuban leader\u2019s death - The Boston Globe|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> and at the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.nd.edu/news/arturo-sandoval-returns-to-notre-dame-for-concert-halftime-performance-in-support-of-christmas-album/|title=Arturo Sandoval returns to Notre Dame for concert, halftime performance in support of Christmas album|publisher=University of Notre Dame|website=Notre Dame News|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2013, President [[Barack Obama]] presented Sandoval with the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trumpetguild.com/content/itg-news/378-arturo-sandoval-receives-presidential-medal-of-freedom|title=Arturo Sandoval receives Presidential Medal of Freedom|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2020|website=International Trumpet Guild|publisher=International Trumpet Guild|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nhi there\n\n==Other work==\nIn 2015, Arturo Sandoval joined the 14th annual Independent Music Awards judging panel to assist independent musicians' careers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2015/07/16/the-14th-annual-independent-music-awards-winners-announced/|title=The 14th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> He was also a judge for the 10th,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2011/02/16/10th-annual-independent-music-awards-nominees-announced/|title=The 10th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=February 16, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> 12th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2013/03/19/12th-annual-independent-music-awards-nominees-announced/|title=The 12th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=March 19, 2013|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> and 13th Independent Music Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2014/03/17/13th-annual-independent-music-awards-nominees-announced/|title=The 13th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=March 17, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n*1982: ''[[To a Finland Station]]'' with [[Dizzy Gillespie]] ([[Pablo Records|Pablo]])\n*1983: ''Breaking the Sound Barrier''\n*1986: ''No Problem'' (Jazz House)\n*1986: ''Tumbaito'' (Messidor)\n*1988: ''Straight Ahead'' (Jazz House)\n*1991: ''[[Flight to Freedom]]'' ([[GRP Records|GRP]])\n*1992: ''[[I Remember Clifford (album)|I Remember Clifford]]'' (GRP)\n*1993: ''Dream Come True'' with [[Michel Legrand]] (GRP)\n*1993: ''[[Danz\u00f3n (Dance On)|Danz\u00f3n]]'' (GRP)\n*1994: ''Cubano''\n*1994: ''The Classical Album'' (RCA)\n*1995: ''Swing Love'' (Babacan)\n*1995: ''Concerto'' (Babacan)\n*1995: ''Arturo Sandoval & the Latin Train'' (GRP)\n*1996: ''[[Swingin' (Arturo Sandoval album)|Swingin']]''<ref>''Music Hound Jazz'' ed. Steve Holtje, Music Hound, Nancy Ann Lee: 2001 \"Sandoval returned to straight-ahead jazz with Swingin'\"</ref> (GRP)\n*1998: ''[[Hot House (Arturo Sandoval album)|Hot House]]'' ([[N-Coded Music|N-Coded]])\n*1999: ''Americana'' (N-Coded)\n*2000: ''Ronnie Scott's Jazz House'' (DCC)\n*2001: ''[[For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story]]'' (Jellybean)\n*2001: ''L. A. Meetings'' (Cubop)\n*2001: ''My Passion for the Piano'' ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]])\n*2003: ''From Havana With Love''\n*2003: ''Trumpet Evolution'' (Westwind)\n*2005: ''Live at the Blue Note'' ([[Half Note Records|Half Note]])\n*2007: ''[[Rumba Palace]]'' ([[Telarc International Corporation|Telarc]])\n*2010: ''[[A Time for Love (Arturo Sandoval album)|A Time for Love]]'' ([[Concord Jazz]])\n*2012: ''[[Dear Diz (Every Day I Think of You)]]'' (Concord Jazz)\n*2014: ''At Middleton'' (film score) (Perseverance)\n*2014: ''Eternamente Manzanero'' with [[Jorge Calandrelli]] (Perseverance)<ref name=\"AM discog\">{{cite web|title=Arturo Sandoval {{!}} Album Discography {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/arturo-sandoval-mn0000575122/discography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref>\n*2018: ''Ultimate Duets''\n*2018: ''Christmas at Notre Dame''\n\n===As sideman===\n[[Image:Arturo Sandoval 1984.jpg|thumb|240px|Arturo Sandoval at the International Jazz Festival, [[Prague]], Lucerna Music Hall, 1984]]\n'''With [[Gloria Estefan]]'''\n*1991 ''Into the Light''\n*1993 ''M\u00ed Tierra''\n\n'''With the [[GRP All-Star Big Band]]'''\n*1992 ''GRP All-Star Big Band'' \n*1993 ''[[Dave Grusin Presents GRP All-Star Big Band Live!]]''\n*1994 ''[[All Blues (GRP All-Star Big Band album)|All Blues]]''\n\n'''With [[Dave Grusin]]'''\n*1994 ''The Orchestral Album''\n*1997 ''West Side Story''\n*1999 ''Random Hearts'' \n*2010 ''An Evening with Dave Grusin''\n\n'''With [[Ed Calle]]'''\n*1996 ''Double Talk''\n*1999 ''Sunset Harbor''\n*2001 ''Twilight''\n\n'''With others'''\n{{div col}}\n*1992 ''Red Sun'', [[Dave Valentin]]\n*1992 ''Tiempo Al Tiempo'', [[Danny Rivera]]\n*1993 ''Duets'', [[Frank Sinatra]]\n*1993 ''How Do You Keep the Music Playing'', [[Johnny Mathis]]\n*1993 ''Michel Plays Legrand'', [[Michel Legrand]]\n*1993 ''Passion'', [[Regina Belle]]\n*1994 ''Noel'', [[Canadian Brass]]\n*1995 ''Moody's Party'', [[James Moody (saxophonist)|James Moody]]\n*1995 ''From Havana with Love'', [[Irakere]]\n*1996 ''Amigos'', [[Paul Anka]]\n*1996 ''25 Years'', [[George Gruntz]]\n*1999 ''What Does It Take?'', [[Candy Dulfer]]\n*1999 ''The Heart of a Legend'', [[Chico O'Farrill]]\n*2001 ''Swingin' for the Fences'', [[Gordon Goodwin's Big Phat Band]]\n*2000 ''Art and Life'', [[Beenie Man]]\n*2002 ''Este Camino Largo'', [[Paquito D'Rivera]]\n*2004 ''The Doble Gigante: The Latin Jazz Sides'', [[Chucho Vald\u00e9s]]\n*2011 ''Duets II'', [[Tony Bennett]]\n*2013 ''My Funny Valentine: The Chet Baker Songbook'', [[Matt Dusk]]\n*2014 ''Ske-Dat-De-Dat: The Spirit of Satch'', [[Dr. John]]\n*2015 ''Passion World'', [[Kurt Elling]]\n*2016 ''Full Circle'', [[Brian Bromberg]]\n*2018 ''Arturo Sandoval'', [[Ariana Grande]]<ref name=\"AM credits\">{{cite web|title=Arturo Sandoval {{!}} Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/arturo-sandoval-mn0000575122/credits|website=AllMusic|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref>\n*2018 ''Street Player'', featured  trumpet solo on 'Chicagovich II' Leonid & Friends (Russian Chicago cover band)\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n*1987: ''A Night in Havana: Dizzy Gillespie in Cuba''\n*1990: ''Dizzy Gillespie and the United Nations Orchestra''\n*1993: ''GRP All-Star Big Band Live''<ref name=\"New Grove\" />\n*1995: ''Lava Lava!''\n*1996: ''Mr. Wrong''\n*1996: ''The Perez Family''\n*2000: ''[[For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story]]''\n*2000: ''Knockout''\n*2001: ''61*''\n*2010: ''Sacred Waters''\n*2011: ''Oscar's Cuba''\n*2013: ''1000 to 1''\n*2013: ''Antebellum''\n*2013: ''At Middleton''\n*2013: ''Christmas in Conway''\n*2013: ''The Resurrection of Malchus''\n*2013: ''Tightwire''\n*2015: ''[[Underdog Kids]]''\n*2018: ''[[The Mule (2018 film)|The Mule]]''\n*2019: ''[[Richard Jewell (film)|Richard Jewell]]''\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cuba|Jazz|Latin music}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050212091902/http://www.mp3.com/arturo-sandoval/artists/6341/biography.html Mp3.com's biography]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080212171206/http://www.mp3.com/albums/582320/summary.html Streaming music]\n*[http://www.tomasitocruz.com/en/ Performing With Tomasito Cruz]\n*[http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1069388/arturo-sandoval-a-time-for-love Arturo Sandoval, \"A Time for Love\"] by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n*[https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/arturo-sandoval Arturo Sandoval Interview] NAMM Oral History Program, July 26, 2011\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandoval, Arturo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Latin jazz trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Crossover jazz trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Cuban jazz trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cuban emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:GRP Records artists]]\n[[Category:Ubiquity Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Calabasas, California]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:American Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:GRP All-Star Big Band members]]\n[[Category:Florida International University faculty]]\n[[Category:Whitworth University faculty]]\n[[Category:Irakere members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban jazz trumpeter, pianist and composer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Arturo Sandoval\n| image            = Arturo Sandoval photo.jpg\n| caption          = Sandoval performing in 2008\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = 6 November 1949 (Age 70)\n| birth_place      = [[Artemisa]], Cuba\n| genre            = [[Jazz]], [[Latin Jazz]], [[Afro-Cuban]]\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Trumpet, Piano, Timbales\n| years_active     = 1977\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = [[Irakere]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[GRP All-Star Big Band]]\n| website          = {{URL|arturosandoval.com}}\n}}\n'''Arturo Sandoval''' is a [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]] [[jazz]] trumpeter, pianist and composer.\n\nSandoval, while living in his native [[Cuba]], was influenced by jazz musicians [[Charlie Parker]], [[Clifford Brown]], and [[Dizzy Gillespie]], finally meeting Gillespie later in 1977. Gillespie became a mentor and colleague, playing with Sandoval in concerts in Europe and Cuba and later featuring him in the United Nations Orchestra. Sandoval defected while touring with Gillespie in 1990, and he became an American [[naturalized citizen]] in 1998.\n\nHis life was the subject of the film ''[[For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story]]'' (2000), starring [[Andy Garc\u00eda]]. Sandoval has won ten [[Grammy Awards]] and been nominated nineteen times; he has also received six [[Billboard Awards|''Billboard'' Awards]] and one [[Emmy Award]]. Additionally, Sandoval has performed in a [[List of Super Bowl halftime shows|Super Bowl Halftime Show]] (1995),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-04-23-ca-51420-story.html|title=Trumpeter Arturo Sandoval Is Denied U.S. Citizenship|author=Clary, Mike|date=April 23, 1997|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> in an [[Orange Bowl]] (2009)<ref>{{Citation|last=SMS PTY|title=Arturo Sandoval Orange Bowl 2009|date=January 1, 2009|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G_Q1zNstmSY|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> at the [[White House]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/11/28/castro-critic-was-playing-scullers-when-learned-former-cuban-leader-death/N2vTTtsG08gaK10v9AOlGP/story.html|title=A Castro critic was playing Scullers when he learned of the former Cuban leader\u2019s death - The Boston Globe|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> and at the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.nd.edu/news/arturo-sandoval-returns-to-notre-dame-for-concert-halftime-performance-in-support-of-christmas-album/|title=Arturo Sandoval returns to Notre Dame for concert, halftime performance in support of Christmas album|publisher=University of Notre Dame|website=Notre Dame News|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2013, President [[Barack Obama]] presented Sandoval with the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trumpetguild.com/content/itg-news/378-arturo-sandoval-receives-presidential-medal-of-freedom|title=Arturo Sandoval receives Presidential Medal of Freedom|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2020|website=International Trumpet Guild|publisher=International Trumpet Guild|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nSandoval was born in [[Artemisa]]. As a twelve-year-old boy in Cuba, Sandoval played trumpet with street musicians. He helped establish the Orquesta Cubana de Musica Moderna, which became the band [[Irakere]] in 1973. He toured worldwide with his own group in 1981. The following year he toured with [[Dizzy Gillespie]], who became his friend and mentor. From 1982 to 1984, Sandoval was voted as Cuba's Best Instrumentalist and was a guest artist at the [[BBC Symphony Orchestra|BBC]] and [[Saint Petersburg Philharmonic Orchestra|Leningrad Symphony Orchestra]]s.<ref name=ucla>{{cite news|url=https://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/Legendary-Cuban-Jazz-Trumpeter-2230|title=Legendary Cuban Jazz Trumpeter Arturo Sandoval, Acclaimed Puerto Rican Saxophonist David Sanchez Perform at UCLA's Royce Hall April 22|author=Nicole Cavazos|publisher=UCLA|date=March 27, 2001|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> In 1989, Gillespie invited Sandoval to be part of the United Nations Orchestra. During a tour with this group, Sandoval visited the American Embassy in Rome to defect from Cuba. He became an American citizen on December 7, 1998.<ref name=\"New Grove\">{{cite book|author=Diaz Ayala, Crist\u00f3bal|author2=Kernfeld, Barry|editor1=Kernfeld, Barry|title=The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz|year=2002|publisher=Grove's Dictionaries Inc.|location=New York|isbn=1-56159-284-6|page=499|volume=3|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nSandoval has performed [[Latin jazz]] with [[Paquito D'Rivera]], [[Tito Puente]], and [[Chico O'Farrill]], [[Cuban music]] in Miami, and [[classical music]] in England and Germany. In the 1990s, he was a member of the [[GRP All-Star Big Band]].<ref name=\"New Grove\"/>\n\nSandoval's song \"A Mis Abuelos\" (To My Grandparents) received Grammy Award nominations for Best Instrumental Composition and Best Arrangement. This composition was featured on his Grammy-winning album, ''Danzon''. Other highlights from Sandoval's discography featuring his compositions include ''[[Dear Diz (Every Day I Think of You)]]'' (2012), ''Live at the Blue Note'' (2005), ''Rumba Palace'' (Grammy 2007), and ''Hot House'' (Grammy 1998).<ref name=grammy>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/arturo-sandoval|title=Arturo Sandoval|publisher=Grammys|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sandoval had performed at [[Eastman Theatre]] along with [[Zane Musa]], [[David Siegel (musician)|Dave Siegel]], Teymur Phel, Johnny Friday, and [[Armando Arce]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Kelly Mullaney|work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|date=October 28, 2014|url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/conxion/2014/10/28/grammy-winner-and-cuban-jazz-legend-arturo-sandoval-comes-to-rochester/18066167/|title=Grammy Winner and Cuban Jazz Legend Arturo Sandoval comes to Rochester|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis 2018 album ''Ultimate Duets'' features a self-titled collaboration with [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Ariana Grande]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Helman, Peter|date=May 4, 2018|title=Arturo Sandoval & Pharrell Williams \u2013 \"Arturo Sandoval\" (Feat. Ariana Grande)|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1994676/arturo-sandoval-pharrell-williams-arturo-sandoval-feat-ariana-grande/music/|work=Stereogum|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe currently resides in [[Miami]], Florida,<ref name=ucla/> where he is a professor at the [[Florida International University]] and a visiting professor to the [[Whitworth University]] where he is in charge of its Jazz Ensemble.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitworth.edu/Academic/Department/Music/PerformanceOpportunities/JazzEnsemble/GuestArtists/ArturoSandoval.htm|title=Guest Artist: Arturo Sandoval|publisher=Whitworth University|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> Prior to his appointment, he was performing worldwide with [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], [[Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra|Pittsburgh Symphony]] and [[National Symphony Orchestra]]s.<ref name=ucla/>\n\n===Films and television===\n{{unfocused|date=May 2019}}\n[[Image:Arturo Sandoval performs during a White House reception.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Sandoval in the East Room of the White House, celebrating Hispanic Heritage Month, October 12, 2001]]\n\nWhen HBO Films developed a film based on Sandoval's life, he was asked to score the movie, which earned him his first Emmy award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/love-or-country-arturo-sandoval-story|title=For Love Or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story|publisher=Emmys|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> In 1996, Sandoval was commissioned by the Kennedy Center Ballet to score ''Pepito's Story'', a ballet based on the book by Eugene Fern and choreographed by [[Debbie Allen]]. Sandoval also composed a classical trumpet concerto that he performed and recorded with the [[London Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=ucla/>\n\nSandoval's compositions and performances can be heard in ''[[The Mambo Kings]]'', which was nominated for a Grammy in 1992 for Best Instrumental Composition written for a Motion Picture or for Television.<ref name=grammy/>\n\nA 2017 television commercial for the Apple iPhone 7 called \"Dive\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mDQlhW-fgDs|title=iPhone 7 \u2013 Dive \u2013 Apple [HD]|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> features Sandoval's \"La Virgen de la Macarena\".\n\nArturo Sandoval has acted in ''For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story''. He has composed music for the films ''The Mule, [[Richard Jewell (film)|Richard Jewell]], A Middleton, The Perez Family, 1000 to 1, For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story'', and ''Underdog Kids''.\n\n==Other work==\nIn 2015, Arturo Sandoval joined the 14th annual Independent Music Awards judging panel to assist independent musicians' careers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2015/07/16/the-14th-annual-independent-music-awards-winners-announced/|title=The 14th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> He was also a judge for the 10th,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2011/02/16/10th-annual-independent-music-awards-nominees-announced/|title=The 10th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=February 16, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> 12th<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2013/03/19/12th-annual-independent-music-awards-nominees-announced/|title=The 12th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=March 19, 2013|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> and 13th Independent Music Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentmusicawards.com/blog/2014/03/17/13th-annual-independent-music-awards-nominees-announced/|title=The 13th Annual Independent Music Awards Winners Announced|publisher=Independent Music Awards|date=March 17, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n*1982: ''[[To a Finland Station]]'' with [[Dizzy Gillespie]] ([[Pablo Records|Pablo]])\n*1983: ''Breaking the Sound Barrier''\n*1986: ''No Problem'' (Jazz House)\n*1986: ''Tumbaito'' (Messidor)\n*1988: ''Straight Ahead'' (Jazz House)\n*1991: ''[[Flight to Freedom]]'' ([[GRP Records|GRP]])\n*1992: ''[[I Remember Clifford (album)|I Remember Clifford]]'' (GRP)\n*1993: ''Dream Come True'' with [[Michel Legrand]] (GRP)\n*1993: ''[[Danz\u0